d"},"en":{"1739–14 Aug 1783":"1739–14 August 1783","1738–1796":"1738–1796","1717–Male":"1717–Deceased","1760–1763":"1760–1763","1763–Female":"1763–Deceased","1765–Female":"1765–Deceased","1767–Male":"1767–Deceased","1770–Male":"1770–Deceased","1739–1783":"1739–1783","25 MAR 1763":"25 March 1763","1770":"1770","14 Aug 1783":"14 August 1783","07 MAR 1765":"7 March 1765","16 Jun 1767":"16 June 1767","1767":"1767","26 Nov 1763":"26 November 1763","1765":"1765","9 April 1770":"9 April 1770","1763":"1763","1796":"1796","1783":"1783","1760":"1760","1739":"1739","1717":"1717","1738":"1738","Evangelisch-Reformierte Kirche, Gangloff, Bayern, Germany":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","Pirmasens, Pirmasens, Bavaria, Germany":"Pirmasens, Pirmasens, Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mohr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived in a fen, Middle Low German <i>mōr</i>.","German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Danish, and Dutch (of German origin): nickname for a man of swarthy complexion, from Middle High German <i>mōr</i>, German <i>Mohr</i>, and Middle Dutch <i>moor</i> ‘Moor’.","German: from a short form of an old personal name, <i>Morhart</i> (see   Morath  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mor","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Ari, Arie, Avi, Eliezer, Erez, Etty, Haim, Hedva, Ilan, Itai, Moshe, Noam.","Jewish (Israeli): shortened and Hebraicized form of some original Ashkenazic surname starting in <i>Mor-</i>.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Mohr   2."]},{"name":"Morath","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Gaston.  German Erhardt, Kurt.","South German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Morhart</i> (see   Morhardt  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace)."]},{"name":"Moerke","meanings":["German (<b>Mörke</b>): variant of <b>Möhrke</b>, from a diminutive of   Mohr  ."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Margaret Mohr was born in 1739. She was buried in Pirmasens, Pirmasens, Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany."},"et":{"1739–14 Aug 1783":"1739–14. august 1783","1738–1796":"1738–1796","1717–Male":"1717–Surnud","1760–1763":"1760–1763","1763–Female":"1763–Surnud","1765–Female":"1765–Surnud","1767–Male":"1767–Surnud","1770–Male":"1770–Surnud","1739–1783":"1739–1783","25 MAR 1763":"25. märts 1763","1770":"1770","14 Aug 1783":"14. august 1783","07 MAR 1765":"7. märts 1765","16 Jun 1767":"16. juuni 1767","1767":"1767","26 Nov 1763":"26. november 1763","1765":"1765","9 April 1770":"9. aprill 1770","1763":"1763","1796":"1796","1783":"1783","1760":"1760","1739":"1739"